          "method": "POST",
          "postData": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "params": [],
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5\",\"temperature\":0,\"stream\":false,\"max_tokens\":2048,\"thinking\":{\"type\":\"disabled\"},\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Explain why this is funny: Why don't scientists trust atoms?\\n\\nBecause they make up everything!\"}]}"
          },
          "queryString": [],
          "url": "https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages"
        },
        "response": {
          "bodySize": 1172,
          "content": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 1172,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_016uMw6uX26E62Zv2wva8Dpj\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"# The Humor Breakdown\\n\\nThis joke works through **wordplay on double meanings**:\\n\\n1. **\\\"Make up\\\"** has two definitions:\\n   - *Literal*: Atoms physically compose/constitute all matter\\n   - *Figurative*: To invent or tell lies\\n\\n2. **The setup** (\\\"Why don't scientists trust atoms?\\\") primes you to expect a reason related to atoms' actual behavior or properties.\\n\\n3. **The punchline** subverts that expectation by pivoting to the slang meaning—suggesting atoms are *dishonest* rather than explaining actual chemistry.\\n\\nThe humor comes from that **surprise twist** combined with the clever way both meanings fit perfectly. It's a clean, accessible pun that works even for people who don't know much science, which is why it's become such a classic joke.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":28,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":187,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
          },
